<div class="message assistant" id="msg-2025-12-14T19-00-23-673Z"><div class="message-header"><span class="role-label">Assistant</span><a href="#msg-2025-12-14T19-00-23-673Z" class="timestamp-link"><time datetime="2025-12-14T19:00:23.673Z" data-timestamp="2025-12-14T19:00:23.673Z">2025-12-14T19:00:23.673Z</time></a></div><div class="message-content">
<div class="assistant-text"><h2>Hybrid Capture Metagenomics: How It Works</h2>
<h3>The Core Problem</h3>
<p>FGT samples are brutal for metagenomics:
- <strong>90-99% human DNA</strong> in many samples
- Shotgun sequencing wastes most reads on host
- To get 10M bacterial reads, you might need 100M+ total reads
- Cost scales linearly with this inefficiency</p>
<h3>The Solution: Capture Enrichment</h3>
<p>Hybrid capture uses synthetic oligonucleotide probes (typically 80-120bp) that are complementary to your targets of interest. These probes are biotinylated, allowing you to physically pull down the sequences you want.</p>
<pre><code>                    WORKFLOW OVERVIEW

     Total DNA from FGT sample
     (95% human, 5% bacterial)
                │
                ▼
     Fragment to ~300-500bp
     Add sequencing adapters
                │
                ▼
     Denature (make single-stranded)
                │
                ▼
     Hybridize with biotinylated probes
     (probes complementary to bacterial targets)
                │
      ┌─────────┴─────────┐
      │                   │
   Bacterial           Human DNA
   fragments           (no probes
   with probes         bound)
   hybridized             │
      │                   │
      ▼                   ▼
   Streptavidin        WASHED
   magnetic beads      AWAY
   pull down              
   biotinylated           
   complexes              
      │
      ▼
   Wash stringently
   (remove non-specific binding)
      │
      ▼
   Elute captured fragments
      │
      ▼
   PCR amplify (optional, low cycles)
      │
      ▼
   Sequence
   (now 70-95% bacterial)
</code></pre>
<h3>Enrichment Efficiency</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Sample type</th>
<th>Pre-capture bacterial</th>
<th>Post-capture bacterial</th>
<th>Fold enrichment</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Low host</td>
<td>30%</td>
<td>90%</td>
<td>3x</td>
</tr>
<tr>
