<td>70-80x</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Very high host</td>
<td>0.1%</td>
<td>50-60%</td>
<td>500-600x</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The worse your starting material, the more capture helps.</p>
<h3>Probe Design Strategy for FGT</h3>
<p><strong>Option 1: Whole genome probes</strong></p>
<p>Design probes tiling across complete genomes of target organisms:</p>
<pre><code>Target species list (example):
├── Lactobacillus crispatus (complete genome, ~2.0 Mb)
├── Lactobacillus iners (~1.3 Mb)
├── Lactobacillus jensenii (~1.5 Mb)
├── Lactobacillus gasseri (~1.9 Mb)
├── Gardnerella vaginalis (~1.6 Mb)
├── Gardnerella leopoldii (~1.5 Mb)
├── Gardnerella swidsinskii (~1.5 Mb)
├── Gardnerella piotii (~1.5 Mb)
├── Prevotella bivia (~2.5 Mb)
├── Prevotella amnii (~2.3 Mb)
├── Atopobium vaginae (~1.4 Mb)
├── Sneathia amnii (~1.3 Mb)
├── Sneathia sanguinegens (~1.4 Mb)
├── Megasphaera type 1 (~2.0 Mb)
├── Megasphaera type 2 (~1.9 Mb)
├── Mycoplasma hominis (~0.7 Mb)
├── Mycoplasma genitalium (~0.6 Mb)
├── BVAB1 (Candidatus Lachnocurva vaginae)
├── BVAB2
├── BVAB3
└── ... (20-40 species total)

Total target space: ~40-60 Mb
Probe count: ~300,000-500,000 probes (80bp, 2x tiling)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Option 2: Conserved gene probes (more economical)</strong></p>
<p>Target universal + discriminatory genes only:</p>
<pre><code>Per organism:
├── cpn60 (full gene, ~1.6 kb)
├── rpoB (full gene, ~4 kb)
├── 16S rRNA (full gene, ~1.5 kb)
├── 23S rRNA (partial, ~1 kb)
├── recA (~1 kb)
├── gyrB (~2 kb)
└── Species-specific markers (~2-5 kb)

Plus functional genes of interest:
├── Sialidases (nanH family)
├── Cytolysins (vly, ily)
├── Lactate dehydrogenases
├── Biogenic amine genes
└── AMR genes

Total target space: ~2-5 Mb
Probe count: ~20,000-50,000 probes
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Option 3: Hybrid approach (recommended)</strong></p>
<pre><code>Full genome coverage:
├── Top 10 most abundant/important species (full genomes)
└── ~20 Mb target space

Conserved gene coverage:
├── Next 30-50 species (marker genes only)
└── ~5 Mb target space

Functional gene panel:
├── All known variants of key genes
└── ~1-2 Mb target space

Total: ~25-30 Mb, ~200,000-250,000 probes
</code></pre>
<h3>How Strain Resolution Works with Capture</h3>
<p>This is where it gets powerful. Unlike amplicons that give you one short region, capture gives you <strong>multiple genomic regions per organism</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Example: Two L. crispatus strains in same sample

                    Strain A genome                 Strain B genome
                    ────────────────                ────────────────
Region 1 (cpn60):   ATGCGATCGATCG...               ATGCGATCGATCG...  (identical)
Region 2 (CRISPR):  CRISPR-A-specific              CRISPR-B-specific (different)
Region 3 (prophage):Present                        Absent
Region 4 (surface): Variant A                      Variant B
Region 5 (metabolic):Gene X present               Gene X absent

Capture recovers ALL of these regions
→ Computational deconvolution identifies both strains
→ Can track which strain dominates over time
→ Can associate specific strains with outcomes
</code></pre>
<p>Tools like <strong>StrainGE</strong>, <strong>StrainPhlAn</strong>, <strong>inStrain</strong>, or <strong>MIDAS2</strong> can resolve strains from this data.</p>
<h3>Practical Protocol</h3>
<p><strong>Day 1: Library Prep</strong></p>
<pre><code>1. Extract DNA (your existing protocol)
2. Quantify (Qubit)
3. Fragment to 350-500bp (Covaris or enzymatic)
4. End repair + A-tailing
5. Adapter ligation (unique dual indexes)
6. Size selection (beads or gel)
7. Pre-capture PCR (6-8 cycles)
8. QC: Bioanalyzer + qPCR
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Day 2: Capture</strong></p>
<pre><code>1. Pool 8-16 libraries (equal mass, ~500ng total)
2. Add blocking oligos (block adapters + human Cot-1)
3. Denature (95°C, 5 min)
4. Add probe pool
5. Hybridize (65-68°C, 16-24 hours)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Day 3: Wash + Sequence</strong></p>
<pre><code>1. Bind to streptavidin beads
2. Stringent washes (increasing temperature)
3. Elute captured DNA
4. Post-capture PCR (8-12 cycles)
5. QC: Bioanalyzer + qPCR
6. Pool for sequencing
7. Sequence: NovaSeq S4, 2x150bp
</code></pre>
<h3>Expected Performance for FGT Samples</h3>
