## Key Findings

### AI-Powered Primer Design
PrimeGen is an orchestrated multi-agent system powered by large language models, designed to streamline labour-intensive primer design tasks for targeted next-generation sequencing. PrimeGen uses GPT-4o as a central controller to engage with experimentalists for task planning and decomposition, coordinating various specialized agents to execute distinct subtasks.(no content)Experimental demonstrations showed that PrimeGen can accommodate up to 955 amplicons, ensuring high amplification uniformity and minimizing dimer formation.

### Primer Design Importance for Microbiome Accuracy
The most widespread microbiota profiling method is based on amplification and sequencing of a variable portion of the 16S rRNA gene as a universal taxonomic marker. Despite its popularity and obvious advantages, this 16S rRNA gene-based approach comes with some important limitations. In particular, the choice of the primer pair for amplification plays a major role in defining the accuracy of the reconstructed bacterial profiles.

### Contamination Reduction Strategies
The amplification and sequencing of nontarget DNA is a particular challenge for microbial ecologists studying host-associated symbionts. For instance, botanists interested in the bacteria within plants must contend with chloroplast DNA (cpDNA), which is amplified by many commonly used rRNA primers. Indeed, in some cases, 90% or more of reads recovered from plant tissues are cpDNA.(no content)While 1391f is predicted to bind more Excavata, Amoebozoa, and Alveolata genes, V9-9_F performed better for Stramenopiles, Rhizaria, Nematoda, and Platyhelminthes, with an additional advantage of low predicted binding to bacterial rRNA genes, reducing contamination.(no content)The recovery of human amplicons in analyses suggests that host contamination may restrict a more comprehensive sampling of eukaryotic microbiota. Strategies such as human DNA blocking primers are needed to reduce host DNA signal.

### Best Practices for Primer Selection
A good method for selecting primer is to evaluate their specificity and overall coverage using real samples or electronic PCR based on the SILVA database and on host factors including the presence of chloroplasts, mitochondria, ribosomes, and other potential sources of non-specific amplification.(no content)An optimized protocol for amplicon-based microbiome profiling uses a modular, two-step PCR process that provides versatility as a common set of indexing primers can be paired with many sets of marker gene specific primers. This protocol is designed for high-throughput and incorporates best practices that substantially increase accuracy compared to existing methods and also minimize the dropout of taxa that have mismatches to the amplification primers.

### Quality Control Measures
Optimization of primer sequences and reaction conditions helps balance amplification across the entire genome, resulting in more accurate sequencing data. Strict quality control (QC) is essential to ensure amplicon purity and integrity before library preparation.(no content)Attempts at optimizing the template amount, primer concentrations, and annealing conditions may yield success, thereby further reducing the time and cost associated with multi-amplicon sequencing-based microbiome studies.


