## PNA and LNA Blocking Oligonucleotides for Microbiome Studies

### Recent 2025 Research

A January 2025 study in Environmental Microbiome (volume 20, Article number: 14) addressed how acquiring representative bacterial 16S rRNA gene community profiles in plant microbiome studies can be challenging due to excessive co-amplification of host chloroplast and mitochondrial rRNA gene sequences. Peptide Nucleic Acid (PNA) clamps prevent this by blocking PCR primer binding or binding within the amplified region of non-target DNA to stop the function of DNA polymerase.(no content)The study applied a universal chloroplast (p)PNA clamp and a newly designed mitochondria (m)PNA clamp to minimise host chloroplast and mitochondria amplification in 16S rRNA gene amplicon profiles of leaf, bark and root tissue of two oak species. Adding PNA clamps to PCR led to an overall reduction of host chloroplast and mitochondrial 16S rRNA gene sequences of 79%, 46% and 99% in leaf, bark and root tissues, respectively.

### How PNA Clamps Work

PNA clamps are synthetic probes comprising high sequence-specific binding affinity toward DNA. The binding of the PNA clamp prevents DNA polymerase from moving along the target DNA.(no content)PNA oligomers show greater specificity in binding to complementary DNAs, with a PNA/DNA base mismatch being more destabilizing than a similar mismatch in a DNA/DNA duplex. This binding strength and specificity also applies to PNA/RNA duplexes. PNAs are not easily recognized by either nucleases or proteases, making them resistant to degradation by enzymes.

### LNA Blocking Oligonucleotides

When a desired DNA is present at low concentrations relative to nearly identical undesired DNAs, LNAs can block amplification of unwanted DNAs. Researchers have studied the length, number, and positioning of LNA bases to improve blocker effectiveness.(no content)Oligonucleotides 18–24 bases long with LNAs at every other position were most effective. Mismatches at LNA ends had little impact on blocking activity. Single and double mismatches were tolerated with longer blockers, especially if the mismatches were near LNA ends. Shorter LNAs were more selective, with &gt;1 mismatch preventing effective blocking.

### Comparison of Methods

Published host signal reduction (HSR) methods include restriction enzyme digestion, peptide nucleic acid (PNA) clamps, blocking oligonucleotides, and nested blocking primers, each with advantages and disadvantages.(no content)Although PNA clamps have been shown to significantly increase the microbial/plant DNA ratio, there are also indications that application of PNA clamps negatively affects PCR efficiency reducing an overall number of reads. However, other studies have shown that suppression of host DNA amplification using PNA clamps results in less biased microbial community analysis than the application of blocking primers and increases the chance of detecting rare microbial taxa.(no content)PNAs can be used to improve high-throughput 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequencing of plant and soil samples by blocking amplification of contaminant plastid and mitochondrial sequences.


