## Key Findings

### Full-Length 16S rRNA Amplicon Sequencing

Sequencing variable regions of the 16S rRNA gene (≃300 bp) with Illumina technology is commonly used to study the composition of human microbiota. Unfortunately, short reads are unable to differentiate between highly similar species.(no content)A high-throughput amplicon sequencing approach combining unique molecular identifiers (UMIs) with Oxford Nanopore Technologies (ONT) or Pacific Biosciences circular consensus sequencing yields high-accuracy single-molecule consensus sequences of large genomic regions. This approach has been applied to sequence ribosomal RNA operon amplicons (~4,500 bp) and genomic sequences (&gt;10,000 bp) of reference microbial communities with a chimera rate &lt;0.02%.

### Accuracy Comparisons

To reach a mean UMI consensus error rate &lt;0.01%, a UMI read coverage of 15× (ONT R10.3), 25× (ONT R9.4.1) and 3× (Pacific Biosciences circular consensus sequencing) is needed, which provides a mean error rate of 0.0042%, 0.0041% and 0.0007%, respectively.(no content)Applying a final round of Racon polishing after Medaka led to a significant reduction in error rate, producing a mean sequence accuracy of 99.99%.

### ssUMI Workflow (2024)

The ssUMI workflow for high-throughput UMI-based error correction of near full-length 16S rRNA amplicons provided higher sequence accuracy than was observed for PacBio HiFi long reads and Illumina short reads, and reached a similar accuracy to LoopSeq synthetic long reads sequenced on Illumina.

### Nanopore vs. Illumina

The Nanopore data outperformed the Illumina data with respect to the proportion of reads from the faecal samples that could be classified to species. This highlights the improved taxonomic resolution of the long reads.(no content)Nanopore sequencing technology has two crucial properties: long reads and a low up-front cost. It can sequence the full 16S rRNA gene retrieving the information content of all nine hypervariable regions. The cost of a MinION sequencer is a small fraction of that of any Illumina or PacBio sequencing system.

### Full rRNA Operon Sequencing

Using only the full-length 16S rRNA gene, 11.3% of the sequences could be matched at the strain level to a database, and 38.4% assigned at the species level. By using both the 16S and 23S rRNA genes within an operon, 22% could be assigned at the strain level and 72.2% at the species level.

### Cost Considerations

The current projected price per sequence for &gt;Q40 data from rRNA operons is: 0.015 USD (ONT UMI), 0.012 USD (PB CCS), 0.007 USD (PB UMI).

