## Key Findings

### Recent 2025 Publications

A January 2025 study by Tourlousse and Sekiguchi published in ISME Communications describes the design and experimental validation of a set of 12 unique synthetic rRNA operons, called &quot;rDNA-mimics,&quot; to serve as spike-in standards for quantitative profiling of fungal/eukaryotic and bacterial microbiomes.(no content)The rDNA-mimics consist of conserved sequence regions from natural rRNA genes to act as binding sites for common universal PCR primers, and bioinformatically designed variable regions that allow their robust identification in any microbiome sample. All constructs cover multiple rRNA operon regions commonly targeted in fungal/eukaryotic microbiome studies (SSU-V9, ITS1, ITS2, and LSU-D1D2), and two of them also include an artificial segment of the bacterial 16S rRNA gene (SSU-V4) for cross-domain application.(no content)The researchers demonstrated that rDNA-mimics added to extracted DNA or directly to samples prior to DNA extraction precisely reflects the total amount of fungal and/or bacterial rRNA genes in the samples, allowing accurate estimation of differences in microbial loads between samples.

### Another 2025 Study

A February 2025 study in Frontiers in Microbiology supports the significance of precise determination of absolute cell numbers, noting that the spike-in method based on adding synthetic DNA to samples ahead of DNA isolation requires less effort than flow cytometry (FACS). The researchers observed a high degree of comparability between the two methods for calculating absolute abundances.

### Background and Rationale

An important limitation of current 16S-seq procedures is that only relative abundance data are generated. Interpretation of microbial community dynamics based solely on relative abundances can be misleading because fluctuations in the absolute abundance of one species may cause an apparent change in the measured (relative) abundance of other species.(no content)Recently, sequencing has been combined with Q-PCR to generate &quot;Quantitative Sequencing&quot; (QSeq) data. QSeq more accurately estimates the true abundance of taxa, is a more reliable basis for inferring correlation, and can be more reliably related to environmental data to infer community assembly processes.

### Technical Approaches

The spike-in nucleic acid approach facilitates absolute quantification of total bacterial cell count with high precision and consistency. Absolute quantification proves more precise when a pool of multiple synthetic DNA molecules serves as a reference compared to using a singular synthetic DNA molecule.(no content)Obtaining absolute abundance measurements is still technically challenging. Researchers have developed synthetic DNA (synDNA) spike-ins that enable precise and cost-effective absolute quantification of microbiome data by adding defined amounts of synDNAs to the samples.(no content)By combining the total gene abundance obtained from qPCR with the relative proportion of individual taxonomy obtained from amplicon sequencing, the gene abundance of individual taxonomy can be estimated. This method is widely used to elucidate microbial dynamics but is limited by the time required due to different workflows for quantitation and sequencing.


