The female genital tract (FGT) plays a pivotal role in the acquisition of HIV infection in women and heterosexual transmission to men. Although the majority of new infections globally occur in women following exposure to HIV through the mucosal membranes of the FGT, there remain significant gaps in our understanding of the local mucosal factors influencing susceptibility. Our previous work demonstrated that relative to vaginal communities dominated by Lactobacillus crispatus, high diversity vaginal bacterial communities comprised of mixed anaerobes with low Lactobacillus abundance were associated with elevated levels of inflammatory chemokines and cytokines in genital secretions, increased numbers of activated CD4+ T cells (“HIV target cells”) in the cervix, and a greater than four-fold increased risk of HIV acquisition2,3. Importantly, these high risk vaginal bacterial communities were present in two-thirds of young, healthy, black South African women in our FRESH (Females Rising through Education, Support and Health) cohort, suggesting that this risk factor is highly prevalent among South African women of reproductive age3. Furthermore, vaginal microbiota and genital inflammation have been shown to significantly reduce the efficacy of vaginal microbicides for preventing HIV4,5. These findings underscore the critical need to understand the mechanisms by which vaginal microbiota increase genital inflammation and HIV acquisition risk, particularly for women living in sub-Saharan Africa.
To address these knowledge gaps, we will utilize 3600 samples from 1200 FRESH participants with longitudinal blood and genital sampling, including pre-infection samples from 102 women who went on to acquire HIV. In Aim 1.1 we will generate multi-omics datasets characterizing vaginal microbiota utilizing metagenomics, metatranscriptomics, fungal internally transcribed spacer (ITS) sequencing, culturomics, microbial whole genome sequencing (WGS), and metabolomics. We will complement this in Aim 1.2 with a comprehensive characterization of the host FGT by assessing genital inflammatory chemokines and cytokines, cervical flow cytometric cell phenotype, and cervical single cell RNA sequencing (scRNAseq) profiles, combined with in-depth behavioral and demographic metadata. These complex multi-omics datasets will then be integrated in Aim 1.3 following critical quality control, transformation, and imputation of data from each modality. Modern supervised integration techniques will be used to identify multi-omics profiles predictive of genital inflammation and HIV acquisition. Candidate vaginal bacterial strains, functions, and/or metabolites will then be validated in Aim 2 using innovative in vitro and in vivo models, including an organ-on-a-chip model co-developed by the co-PI, cervical and vaginal organoids, and a humanized mouse model. Our preliminary data indicate promising candidates that can already be tested directly. Overall, this project will identify specific bacterial strains and molecules, along with host cellular lineages and sensing pathways, that mediate microbiota-induced genital inflammation and increased HIV acquisition risk. It will also validate much needed novel model systems that test the interactions of microbiota, host, and HIV to provide critical resources to develop the mechanistic understanding needed to advance the field. 
This proposal leverages the complementary expertise of Drs. Doug Kwon and Scott Handley to define the role of vaginal microbiota in genital inflammation and HIV acquisition. Dr. Kwon has studied the vaginal microbiome, mucosal immunology, and HIV pathogenesis, and has extensive experience working with clinical cohorts in sub-Saharan Africa, including over 10 years as the co-PI of the FRESH study. Dr. Handley is an expert in using microbial genomics and metagenomics to understand the impact of microbiota on human diseases. The co-PIs have a long history of productive collaboration, including multiple R01s together and seminal findings on the role of the microbiome in HIV2,6,7. They will work with Drs. Kris Sankaran and Laura Symul, biostatisticians with extensive expertise with latent variable modeling, visualization of multi-omics data, and multi-resolution analysis of the microbiome. In this proposal, we will build on our prior work and utilize an integrated multi-omics approach to address critical questions: 1) what are the specific bacterial strains, mediators and/or functions that induce host genital inflammation, 2) what are the host cellular lineages that sense bacteria in the FGT, 3) what host pathways are triggered by inflammatory bacteria in the FGT, and 4) can inhibitors of host microbial sensing be used to reduce HIV acquisition risk. We will answer these questions using samples from a unique clinical cohort of South African women living in an area of extraordinarily high HIV incidence and prevalence, innovative multi-omic approaches, advance biostatistical methods, a library of primary FGT bacterial isolates, and novel in vitro and in vivo models. This research has the potential to inform strategies for reducing new HIV infections in women, particularly for those living in sub-Saharan Africa. In this proposal, the following Aims will be addressed:
Aim 1: Utilize integrated multi-omics characterization of the female genital tract to identify drivers of genital inflammation and HIV acquisition risk
Aim 2: Investigate candidate pathways of microbiota-mediated genital inflammation and HIV acquisition risk using novel in vitro and in vivo models 
RESEARCH STRATEGY
    SIGNIFICANCE
The central role of the female genital tract (FGT) in HIV transmission. In the over four decades since the identification of HIV as the causative agent of AIDS, HIV has caused over 40 million deaths and left nearly 39 million living with disease8. Of the 1.2 million new infections each year, almost 70% occur in sub-Saharan Africa and most occur in young women of reproductive age. Heterosexual intercourse is responsible for the majority of global HIV transmission, with women being twice as likely to contract HIV through heterosexual sex as men9. Mucosal tissues in the FGT therefore represent the frontline of transmission in most incident infections. Understanding the mucosal environment of the FGT is critical for developing strategies to prevent HIV transmission. Studies in nonhuman primates have shown that soon after HIV exposure, viral replication occurs within tissue resident CD4+ T cells (“HIV target cells”) in the mucosa of the cervix and vagina for 5-7 days prior to systemic dissemination10,11. This early phase has been referred to as a “window of opportunity”, since interventions which reduce the viral reproductive rate (R0) to &lt;1 could prevent systemic viral dissemination12. Effective strategies to prevent HIV in women will require a detailed understanding of the critical mucosal factors in the FGT that modulate HIV susceptibility.
The cervicovaginal microbiome, genital inflammation, and HIV susceptibility. Inflammation in the FGT is associated with an increased risk of HIV infection3,13,14. Cervicovaginal bacteria have been shown to be closely associated with genital inflammation3, but the mechanisms by which specific bacteria increase inflammation and HIV risk remain unclear. We characterized vaginal microbiota in FRESH (Females Rising through Education, Support, and Health), a prospective cohort study of healthy HIV-uninfected South African women monitored for nine months with twice weekly HIV testing. Sequencing of the bacterial 16S rRNA gene from vaginal swabs revealed four cervicovaginal bacterial community types, or “cervicotypes” (CTs), two of which had low diversity and were dominated by either Lactobacillus crispatus (CT1, 9% of participants) or Lactobacillus iners (CT2, 28%), and two high diversity CTs dominated by mixed anaerobes, including Gardnerella vaginalis (CT3, 28%) or other mixed anaerobes (CT4, 35%) (Fig. 1A)2,3. The most abundant taxa in CT4 were Prevotella, Gardnerella, Sneathia and Megasphaera. Individuals with CT3 and CT4 communities were at over 4-fold higher risk of acquiring HIV compared to those with L. crispatus dominance (Fig. 1B)2. This risk was associated with elevated genital cytokine levels3 (Fig. 1C) and a 17-fold increase in the number of cervical HIV target cells (activated tissue resident CD4+ T cells) (Fig. 1D)2, providing a potential biologic mechanism for the observed increase in infection. We identified specific bacterial taxa linked with HIV infection, showing that Prevotella melaninogenica, P. bivia and Sneathia sanguinegens, among other anaerobes, were significantly more abundant in individuals who subsequently acquired HIV2. The specific mechanisms by which FGT bacteria induce genital inflammation and increased HIV risk are unknown. 
The lack of robust testing in model systems. Mechanistic understanding of FGT biology has been limited by the lack of robust testing in model systems. Existing models of host-microbiota interactions in the FGT range from epithelial cells alone in a simple monolayer15 or polarized in a transwell16 to murine models of herpes infection17,18 and a nonhuman primate model of IUD insertion19. Each of these models has critical limitations, and none successfully recapitulate the complex conditions of the genital tract in women20. We propose the use of multiple complementary and innovative models to evaluate mechanisms underlying observed phenotypes in women in FRESH to better understand the most important biological interactions between microbiota, host cells, and HIV infection. Validation of these model systems will lead to much needed mechanistic insight and provide a significant advance for the field.</p>
