<h2>Primer Design Strategy</h2>
<h3>For Published Primers (cpn60)</h3>
<p><strong>cpn60 UT primers (H279p/H280p from Hill lab):</strong></p>
<pre><code>H279p: 5'-GAIIIIGCIGGIGAYGGIACIACIAC-3'
H280p: 5'-YKIYKITCICCRAAICCIGGIGCYTT-3'
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Enhancement:</strong> Add UMI + Illumina adapter tails</p>
<pre><code>UMI-H279p: 5'-[Illumina adapter]-[8N UMI]-GAIIIIGCIGGIGAYGGIACIACIAC-3'
UMI-H280p: 5'-[Illumina adapter]-[8N UMI]-YKIYKITCICCRAAICCIGGIGCYTT-3'
</code></pre>
<h3>For De Novo Design (functional genes)</h3>
<p><strong>Workflow:</strong>
1. Download all available sequences for target gene from NCBI/UniProt
2. Include your isolate sequences as they become available
3. Align with MUSCLE/MAFFT
4. Use DegePrime or ARDEP for degenerate primer design
5. Validate coverage in silico against FGT taxa
6. Consider DPO format for specificity</p>
<p><strong>Example: nanH (sialidase)</strong></p>
<pre><code>Multiple nanH variants exist:
├── nanH1 (Gardnerella vaginalis type)
├── nanH2 (Gardnerella other species)
├── nanH3 (Prevotella)

Design strategy:
├── Conserved regions that capture all variants? OR
├── Variant-specific primers for each?

Recommendation: Start with broad capture, resolve computationally
</code></pre>
